  "prompt": "Why did Bombay turn Mumbai, Calcutta turn Kolkata?",
  "response": "The renaming of cities like Bombay to Mumbai and Calcutta to Kolkata is part of a broader movement in India to reflect local language and culture, particularly post-independence. \n\n1. **Colonial Legacy**: The original names, like Bombay and Calcutta, were derived from colonial influences. Bombay is believed to have been derived from the Portuguese name \"Bomb Aiem,\" meaning \"Good Bay,\" while Calcutta was adapted from the Bengali name \"Kolkata.\"\n\n2. **Cultural Revival**: After India gained independence in 1947, there was a significant movement towards reclaiming indigenous identities and languages. This included renaming cities to restore their original names, which were often changed during British rule.\n\n3. **Official Changes**: The government officially adopted these names to better reflect the cultural heritage and linguistic identity of the local population. Mumbai was adopted in 1995, and Kolkata in 2001, both aimed at honoring the local languages\u2014Marathi for Mumbai and Bengali for Kolkata.\n\nOverall, these changes were emblematic of a larger effort to assert national pride and cultural identity in post-colonial India.",
